# spel -- Clojure Playwright Wrapper

Idiomatic Clojure wrapper for Playwright Java 1.58.0. Two modes: **CLI/daemon** (implicit page, no boilerplate) and **Library** (explicit `page` arg for tests).

## Critical: Always Self-Check the API First

**Before writing any spel code, verify the function exists and check its signature:**

```bash
spel --eval '(println (spel/help "screenshot"))'   # search by keyword
spel --eval '(println (spel/help "spel"))'          # list all spel/ functions
spel --eval '(println (spel/help "snapshot"))'      # list snapshot/ functions
spel --eval '(println (spel/help))'                 # list all namespaces
```

`spel/help` returns function names, arglists, and descriptions. **Always run this before assuming a function signature.** The eval sandbox has 350+ functions across 14 namespaces.

## How It Works: Daemon Mode (Default)

The spel daemon manages a persistent browser session. You send commands and evals against it -- no `start!/stop!` boilerplate needed.

```bash
# Open a page (starts daemon automatically)
spel open https://example.com

# Now the browser is running. All subsequent commands use it:
spel screenshot /tmp/shot.png
spel snapshot                         # accessibility tree (text)
spel annotate /tmp/annotated.png      # annotated screenshot
spel pdf /tmp/page.pdf

# Use --eval for multi-step Clojure scripting (page already available):
spel --eval '
(spel/navigate "https://news.ycombinator.com")
(spel/wait-for-load)
(println "Title:" (spel/title))
(println "Links:" (count (spel/$$ "a")))
(spel/screenshot {:path "/tmp/hn.png"})
'

# Close when done
spel close
```

**No `spel/start!` or `spel/stop!` needed.** The daemon owns the browser session. `--eval` expressions run against the daemon's page directly.

> `spel/start!` / `spel/stop!` exist only for standalone scripts that run without a daemon. For agent exploration, always use daemon mode.

## Verify Your Setup

```bash
spel open https://example.com
spel --eval '(println "Title:" (spel/title)) (println "URL:" (spel/url))'
spel screenshot /tmp/verify.png
spel close
```

If this works, spel is installed correctly.

